<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910628-0013</DOCNO><DOCID>910628-0013.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Ceramics Process Systems Corp.:   Carpenter Agrees to Fund   Study on Firm's Technology</HL><DATE>06/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   CPSX CRS</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>INDUSTRIAL TECHNOLOGY andamp; PRODUCTION, QUALITY CONTROL (ITC)STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)</IN><RE>MASSACHUSETTS (MA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Ceramics Process Systems Corp. said Carpenter TechnologyCorp. agreed to fund a two-year &quot;multimillion dollar&quot;research program on Ceramics Process technology to makeceramic engine parts.   The maker of ceramics products, which is based in Milford,Mass., declined to disclose the exact amount of moneyinvolved. Under the agreement, Carpenter will receive anoption to license Ceramics Process's Quickset injectionmolding technology for making engine parts and certainrelated high-temperature material compositions. Carpenter isa Reading, Pa., maker of specialty steels and metals.</LP><TEXT>   Ceramics Process said the agreement will acceleratedevelopment of its technology for making ceramic parts forturbine, automotive, aerospace and other engines.</TEXT></DOC>